CSE2215 - Computer Graphics 2024-2025 - Final Project

The final project targets a ray tracer and is performed in groups of three. You will be able to find your group via Brightspace. This document is quite detailed to provide a guideline through the tasks and clarify expectations, so please read the entire document carefully before you start.

General information

The project is submitted in various stages. There are two moments, when you need to submit code. The first code submission ensures basic functionalities of your ray tracer. The second code submission is intended for advanced features and leaves more freedom in the choices of what you are going to implement. Each code submission is followed by a submission of an overview of the work distribution within the group, which can be a confirmation or rectification of the initial work distribution, as submitted early in the project.

Deadlines

  • Preliminary work distribution: 20th December 2024, 23:59

  • Code delivery – standard features: 16th January 2025, 23:59

  • Overview of the work attribution (standard features) and report: 17th January 2025, 23:59

  • Code delivery – extra features: 23th January 2025, 23:59

  • Overview of the work attribution (extra features) and report: 24th January 2025, 23:59

To ensure a fair distribution of the work, you are asked to start the project with a work plan for each individual group member. This will ensure that all students can successfully complete the project without generating conflicts in terms of task responsibilities. We facilitated this step by organizing the ray tracer into “features”, which can be attributed to group members. This step is further described below. If you cannot agree on a work distribution, please inform us before this date via course email (cg-cs-ewi@tudelft.nl). After you have uploaded your planning, you may start working on the project (even before the planning deadline). Nevertheless, please take your time for this step. The deadlines for submitting code is always followed by a deadline for submitting the work distribution. This allows you to inspect the submission and verify that all code has been correctly submitted and the workload reflects the actual implementation efforts of each individual.

Below are some general points to keep in mind:

  • Submit all files in a zip-file.

  • Your code must compile on Windows with Visual Studio 2022 (using the default MSVC toolchain, as already required for the previous assignments). We will not grade your code if it does not compile on this platform.

  • Copying code is fraud. This includes code from others or internet sources and holds even if you modify the code or translate it from another language. Using code from last year’s project is not allowed (unless it was written by you alone).

  • Any external resources that you use in the project have to be clearly identified in the report and your code (in the form of comments). Please provide specific links to the websites, YouTube videos, book chapters, articles, etc. that you use (e.g., “Wikipedia” would not be a valid reference for the Wikipedia page of the Phong model. In this case, you should include the direct link to the Phong model page, potentially even the paragraph/section.). The use of external resources might result in a point deduction.

  • Only one common submission is expected per group but the grades are individual based on the work distribution overview. We will use the most recent submission for grading.

  • There will be no presentation of the projects but some groups will be contacted for a post-submission interview. In the case you are interviewed, you can expect to receive an invitation email up to 12 days after you handed in your project. If you are invited, your grade might be withheld until after the meeting. The interview will be scheduled together to make sure everyone is available.

  • Each group member should be able to explain any part of the code that they were involved in. For example, if you contributed to “transparency”, you need to be able to explain all code related to “transparency”. Further, if you have contributed to a feature, you are fully responsible for its content. This includes the situation, where fraud or plagiarism occurs. Working together on a feature implies that everyone involved follows the full development. It is not possible to take responsibility only for a part of a feature and its corresponding code.

  • Each group will be automatically assigned to an EWI GitLab repository. Do not use alternative repositories to develop your code. Do not make your project accessible to anyone outside your group, not even after the project is finished.

  • Final deadline: Please upload early to avoid problems with Brightspace or the internet. You can upload multiple times but only your latest submission will be kept. Note that uploading in the very final minute usually results in issues with Brightspace (please refer to the submission section at the end of the document).

  • In case of unexpected issues, e.g., group members being unresponsive, contact us immediately via the course email (cg-cs-ewi@tudelft.nl) (or reach out during the sessions). Do not wait until the shortly before the deadline. The later we receive the information, the less we can help you.

Grading

The Final Project is graded on a 10 point scale, and counts for 60% of the Practical Grade. There is no minimum grade for the Final Project, but the Practical Grade (combination of assignments and project) needs to be at least a 5.0 to pass the course. The points are distributed between standard and extra features.

The final sum of your points translates directly to your project grade, capped to a maximum of 10 points. We will rely on your work distribution to determine the points of each student.

Your code for the standard features is graded by testing the functions you implement on various inputs. For extra features, grading is performed manually. You will receive a breakdown of your grade in the feedback section on Brightspace.

Your teammates are your first point of contact when questions arise. You should likewise help your teammates when needed.

Initial and Final Planning

During the first days after being assigned to a group, you should meet with your team to discuss the work distribution, i.e., who will work on which feature.

The group will submit the work overview. For the first deadline, this only concerns the standard features. Use the prepared excel sheet for this purpose. Make sure the file is uploaded before the planning deadline. The group will submit the workload distribution again after code is submitted, to confirm or rectify the work distribution. Modifications to the plan need the consent of all team members in case of dispute, reach out via the cg-cs-ewi@tudelft.nl. You always have 24h after the deadline for a work-distribution overview to verify the submitted document. If there is a mistake, you need to notify us within this period. After this, we consider the overview as final.

The grades are automatically computed using this Excel file so, please, do not modify its structure, only fill in the blue cells. Use integer values in the range [0–100] for the percentages. There is an example workload file to serve as reference (do not submit it). The standard features should be distributed as equally as possible to provide a fair workload for all members.

Although it is theoretically possible to successfully complete the project even with zero points gathered from standard features, if compensated by work on extra features, no group member can be attributed less than 5 points of the standard features in the planning. No group member can obtain more than 6.5 points via standard features, independently of the delivered contribution. In other words, you are encouraged to work toegether. In this case, the points are shared among those that contributed to the realization.

For example, assume three members who contributed differently to the realization of a feature with 40%, 30%, and 30%. If the feature was graded to be worth 2.0 points, then these members would receive 0.8, 0.6 and 0.6 points, respectively. Please pay attention to dependencies between features to avoid having to wait for a completion of a feature of someone else before being able to start with yours.

Attention: If you do not contact or react to the other group members 24h before the planning deadline, you might be removed from the group and you might then not be able to participate in the project anymore. The remaining members should still allocate tasks to the non-existent member (at least 5 points), as in some cases the group may receive a replacement member.

Standard features and dependencies are described in Appendix B: Standard Features. They must be implemented as indicated. Do not change method names/arguments and work with the given framework. You can create additional methods, but our grading tests rely on the provided functions. It is a good idea to develop visual debugging components while working on a feature to verify its correctness and to facilitate the discussion with the teaching assistants. In some casees, such debugging tasks are indicated and part of the exercise. Further, features might require you to answer reflection questions in the report.

Once done with the standard features, you can immediately start implementing extra features. However, note that your deliverables related to the standard features have to be submitted by the respective deadline for standard features. You cannot submit these afterwards.

Extra features will be described in Appendix C: Extra Features. However, other ideas for extra features are welcome, and we will consider distributing points for these. If you are in doubt if an idea for an extra feature is “worth it”, please contact us via the course email but assume some delay in our answer – hence, it is useful to first stick to the provided list of features. Do not forget to add a description of all extra features in your corresponding report - what is not presented in the report is not graded.

Framework information

In this project, you will build upon fundamentals that you learned in the lecture and implemented in the assignments to develop a fully functional ray tracer. We provide a framework to get you started, which we briefly present in the following.

The framework’s UI enables you to choose from a selection of test scenes to work with, including a custom scene (this initially loads a scene custom.obj from the data folder). If you like to load your own scene, you can simply overwrite the corresponding custom.obj with your own (please note that you should not rename your obj material file (.mtl), as the original filename is mentioned within the obj file itself).

On BVHInterface, HitInfo, Features, RenderState, and Sampler

The framework is similar to the code you worked with during the Ray Intersection Assignment. However, there are some method arguments and structs, which you should familiarize yourself with. These are:

  • BVHInterface, allows you to run intersection tests against the entire scene using an acceleration structure – the same that you develop in the assignments. For the project, we provide you with a running implementation in binary code that returns information about ray hits in a HitInfo object.

  • HitInfo, defined in common.h, is returned by the various intersection tests, and stores information about a (potential) intersection point. This information is necessary for, e.g., shading, texture lookups, and other material interactions.

  • Features/ExtraFeatures, defined in common.h, are booleans to enable/disable features of the renderer on the fly. Each standard/extra feature you implement has a corresponding Boolean here, and is accessible through the UI. Do not tamper with these Booleans, as we use them during grading to isolate features. You are free to extend the ExtraFeatures object with your own parameters. A particular boolean is enableDebugDraw, which you should test for before executing any debug drawing calls within your code. This avoids drawing calls during the ray tracing process, when they would not serve any purpose.

  • RenderState, defined in render.h, holds handles to Scene, Features and a BVHInterface object. A RenderState is created per render thread at the start of the rendering process, it is passed to most methods you implement and contains the global parameters influencing the rendering process. RenderState also holds a per-thread Sampler object, so you can generate random numbers in a thread-safe manner.

  • Sampler, defined in sampler.h , is generated per render thread, and is a fast, well-distributed pseudo-random number generator, which is compatible with parallel execution, thus please use it instead of rand. This allows you to generate uniformly distributed 1D/2D random numbers.

Code Structure

Most of the framework’s components are separated into header/source files such that you can work on them in isolation. Here is an overview of which files relate to which ray tracer components that you should implement:

  • shading.h/shading.cpp - Your implementation of shading models.

  • recursive.h/recursive.cpp - Your implementations of recursive ray-tracing features.

  • bvh.cpp - Your implementation of the ray traversal through the BVH

  • interpolate.h/interpolate.cpp - Your interpolation implementation of normals and other components.

  • texture.h/texture.cpp - Your implementations of texture sampling features.

  • light.h/light.cpp - Your implementations of light sampling features.

  • render.h/render.cpp - Multi-threaded rendering code, and your implementation of multisampling.

  • extra.h/extra.cpp - Your implementations of most optional extra features.

You do not have to touch the following files to solve the standard features, but you are encouraged to modify these to solve the extra features:

  • common.h - Basic data structures used throughout the application

  • main.cpp - The program launch point and the user interface.

  • draw.h/draw.cpp - Helper methods for visual debugging.

  • scene.h/scene.cpp - Responsible for loading the scene and auxiliary data.

  • your_tests.cpp - Example unit tests that demonstrate the program interface. If left untouched, these should compile and pass for your implementation.

The following files were not described, but you must not modify these, as they will probably break grading tests: fwd.h, bvh_interface.h, sampler.h, config.h/config.cpp, screen.h/screen.cpp, verification.cpp.

Be careful: if you break grading tests because you modified these files, the project will not receive points for the failing features.

As a helpful tool, the file verification.cpp includes some assertions that tell you what component you may have modified, and the file your_tests.cpp shows how components may be used in grading tests.

Compilation

As previously stated, we provide a prebuilt library for the required Windows environment with the reference solutions for the intersection functions as well as most BVH and some shading functions. We have also included binaries for Linux, but we cannot guarantee they will work with your compiler and OS version (you might need to use the solution without the prebuilt binaries in this case).

To start, you can compile the code and test the application. Note that you can compile the code in at least two different modes “DEBUG” or “RELEASE”. When compiled in “DEBUG” mode, there are a lot of additional tests behind the scenes, e.g., if you are accessing a std::vector, it always checks that you stay within its bounds. It is very useful to compile in “DEBUG” mode when developing code to ensure that all these tests are performed. Nevertheless, once the code is working, you should switch to “RELEASE”. If you now compile the code, it will be optimized and results in a significant speedup - especially useful when working with complex scenes. In the same spirit, when in “DEBUG” mode, you should rather work with simpler scenes to avoid long render times. Whichever mode you chose, once compiled, you can launch the application.

On our side, we use MSVC on Windows to compile your project and run tests. With this in mind, you should not use any external libraries (except for the included library Provided.lib).

Rasterization Mode

From the menu, you can choose a Rasterization and a Ray traced view mode. The OpenGL-based Rasterization mode serves for debugging and scene control.

The GUI allows you to insert, remove and otherwise modify light sources, which are only used during Ray traced mode. This means the illumination in Rasterization mode does not correspond to the illumination in Ray traced mode. During Rasterization, we just consider a single light source in the scene to add some illumination.

Visual debugging features are only enabled during the Rasterization mode. See Visual Debugging for more information.

Ray Traced Mode

During the Ray traced mode, the program generates at least one camera ray per pixel. This is bootstrapped by the renderImage() method in render.h/render.cpp. For each camera ray, the renderRay() method in recursive.h/recursive.cpp is called, which computes an RGB color value by determining the light along that ray. The renderRay() method calls other methods such that reflections, shadows, and other effects are considered. We recommend you read both methods to understand them, but you should not have to modify these in your implementation.

While the Ray traced mode traces actual rays for each pixel, you can also click the “Render to file” button to render an image and save it to file directly. This functionality is available in the Rasterization mode, so you can render to a file without switching to Ray traced mode, if the latter is too slow. For simple scenes, the Ray traced mode may be interactive, but as scene and effect complexity increases, ray tracing performance will inevitably slow down – hence, the need for the provided BVH data structure.

Rendering the Cornell Box without any features enabled should result in the following image. If you are using the prebuilt intersect library, you should be able to reproduce this result just by running the program before altering any code.

When a scene is loaded, it is centered and scaled according to the longest axis. Hereby, the placing of the light sources in the scene via the interface is facilitated. Via the interface, you can add light sources, change their type/color or move them around.

Visual Debugging

For some features, you are expected to implement Visual Debugging tools. This is generally the element to start with, and it should aid in verifying the correctness of your implementation. By having visual feedback of calculations, you are able to catch bugs early on. Visual debugging can be implemented in the same methods as the rest of your code. You should make use of the enableDebugDraw variable in the features of the RenderState to test whether the debug drawing should be executed. This variable can be activated and deactivated in the UI. During ray tracing, your debug code will then be ignored, as the variable is set to false, so that it does not interfere with the image generation.

Below are some tips to help you:

  • When you press r in Rasterization mode, a single debug ray is created through the mouse cursor position. By using drawRay() from draw.h/draw.cpp and other draw functions, you will illustrate the debug ray’s traversal through the scene. This allows you to inspect, e.g., reflections, transparency, or visibility tests.

  • The UI library, Dear ImGui allows you to inject your own interfaces and sliders throughout the code. Dear ImGui makes it simple, so we recommend you use it for visual debugging.

  • Experiment with the debugging outputs. For example, you can color a ray to illustrate the current depth with respect to the number of reflections, or you can draw a line to illustrate the normal of each surfaces encountered by the ray.

  • For other features you will need other forms of visual debugging that are not based on drawing rays. You might notice quickly that such visualizations are very useful. Refer to draw.h/draw.cpp for some helper code.

Appendix A - General Remarks

Materials (.MTL)

OBJ files have an optional accompanying MTL file. When you create a model with materials in Blender, the MTL file is also exported together with the OBJ file. Note that some advanced material options in Blender are not supported by the MTL file format. The MTL files are automatically loaded by the framework, since the MTL filename is mentioned in the OBJ file. We have added a Material structure to the framework to allow easy access to material coefficients.


// Defined in framework/mesh.h 

struct Material { 

    glm::vec3 kd; 

    glm::vec3 ks { 0.0f };  

    float shininess { 1.0f }; 

    float transparency { 1.0f }; 

 

    // Pointer to optional diffuse texture 

    std::shared_ptr<Image> kdTexture; 

};

Diffuse coefficient. While you could directly use the kd value for diffuse shading, we suggest that you retrieve the coefficient via a helper method: sampleMaterialKd() in the shading.h file. In case that you have implemented the texture interpolation functions and the model uses a texture, sampleMaterialKd() will return the correct value.


glm::vec3 kd = sampleMaterialKd(state, hitInfo);

Transparency. There is one additional parameter to the material, transparency, which ranges from 0.0 (fully transparent) to 1.0 (fully opaque). Note that, despite its name, this correspondings directly to the alpha component in alpha blending. This should be used for your implementation. In Blender you can set the transparency by going to the Material tab, activating transparency and setting the Alpha value. This value will be exported to the MTL file and imported by the framework.

Multiple materials. If you created a model that uses multiple materials, the mesh will be split into submeshes. The loadMesh method in mesh.cpp actually returns a vector of meshes, and not a single mesh, such that each submesh has its own material properties. Also note that the BVH structure represents the entire scene, and already loops over all submeshes for you. In the end, you can directly access the material object of a (sub)mesh through the HitInfo object.

Drawing debug rays

A ray is defined by its origin, direction, and intersection parameter t, as defined in the Ray Intersection assignment. You can define your own rays for debugging and call the method drawRay from draw.h/draw.cpp to render it in Rasterization mode. This function also draws a small sphere at the intersection point, unless you do not modify the t value (it is set to infinity - i.e. FLOAT_MAX).

Here is an example of how to draw a green ray:


// Define an arbitrary ray and the color green 

If (state.features.enableDebugDraw)  

{ 

Ray ray = { .origin = glm::vec3(1, 0, 2), .direction = glm:vec3(0, 0, 1), .t = 3.0 }; 

glm::vec3 color (0, 1, 0); 

 

// Call drawRay, declared in the `draw.h` file 

drawRay(ray, color);     

}

Drawing debug boxes

In the draw.h/draw.cpp file you can likewise find a method to draw axis-aligned bounding boxes (AABBs):


void drawAABB(const AxisAlignedBox& box, DrawMode drawMode, const glm::vec3& color, float transparency);

The draw mode can be either DrawMode::Filled to render the sides of the AABB, or DrawMode::Wireframe to render only the edges. You can also pass a color and transparency value. This last value can be used with DrawMode::Filled to draw transparent boxes, where 0.0 if fully transparent and 1.0 is fully opaque.

Appendix B - Standard Feature Descriptions

Be sure to read all feature descriptions carefully, including both programming and visual debug tasks.

The visual debug will help you assess the validity of your solutions to the programming tasks. 

Therefore, it can be a good idea to start with the visual debug tasks and proceed in parallel. 



The standard features also include several reflection tasks. You might be asked to investigate and discuss parameters or behavior of a given implementation. 

Besides text (respecting the word count), some questions also require captured images. Keep in mind that, in some cases, using images from the visual debug tasks might be most suitable.

In the following, we will present each of the standard features before tackling the extra features for the second part of the project.

Shading models

Flags: features.enableShading, features.shadingModel, files: shading.h, shading.cpp.

This feature partially repeats work from prior assignments, and requires you to implement a custom shading model. Standard shading models are already provided via the library as binary. You must implement a non-photorealistic model which instead evaluates a piecewise linear function - a gradient function - to determine surface color.

Methods

  • [0.50] - LinearGradient.sample(...), computeLinearGradientModel(...) - The idea is that a LinearGradient is used to color the object. Each entry in the LinearGradient is a boundary position and a corresponding color, referred to as a component. These components are used to encode the colors as bins.

For a number ti between [-1, 1], we determine the two components whose positions englobe ti and linearly interpolate their colors based on ti’s relative position between both. If ti is beyond the smallest/largest components, the nearest component color must be sampled.

In the latter function, given a camera direction, a light direction, a relevant intersection, and a color coming in from the light call the sampling function using the cosine of theta, as defined in the diffuse shading model.

Visual debug tasks and reflection tasks

  • [0.50] Hard-code a LinearGradient and use it to illustrates the difference between the Blinn-Phong and the Phong model (both are provided via the library as a binary) and you can use the shading mode LinearGradientComparison. What colors are good choices for the LinearGradient definition? How many components in the LinearGradient would you minimally suggest? Describe your choice in maximally 50 words. Provide screenshots.

Recursive ray reflections

Flags: features.enableReflections, files: recursive.h, recursive.cpp.

This feature extends the method renderRay(...) to enable recursive specular reflections. Every time a ray intersects a specular surface (read, material.ks is non-zero), you should generate a mirror reflectance ray and evaluate its contribution.

n

Methods

  • [0.25] - generateReflectionRay(...) - Given an incident ray and an intersection point, generate a mirrored ray.

  • [0.25] - renderRaySpecularComponent(...) - Given a camera ray (or secondary ray) and an intersection, compute the contribution of a mirrored ray, by recursively evaluating renderRay(…, depth + 1), and add the result times material.ks to the current intersection’s hit color.

Example renders

Visual debug tasks and reflection tasks

  • [0.25] - Visualize the surface normal at the location, where your ray reflects and the light direction vector. Also visualize secondary rays with different colors.

Recursive ray transparency

Flags: features.enableTransparency, files: recursive.h, recursive.cpp.

This feature extends the method renderRay(...) to enable recursive transparent passthrough. Every time a ray intersects a transparent surface (read, material.transparency is smaller one), you should continue along the ray (passthrough ray), evaluate its contribution, and correctly alpha-blend the results.

Methods

  • [0.25] - generatePassthroughRay(...) - Given an incident ray and a intersection point, generate a passthrough ray for transparency, starting at the intersection point and continuing in the same direction.

  • [0.50] - renderRayTransparentComponent(...) - Given a camera ray (or reflected camera ray) and an intersection, compute the contribution of a passthrough transparent ray, recursively evaluating renderRay(…, depth + 1) along this ray, and correctly alpha-blend the result with the current intersection’s hit color.

Example renders

Visual debug tasks and reflection tasks

  • [0.5] - Visualize passthrough rays using the blended color, illustrate the intersection points, and show properties of the intersected surface (transparency, kd) in a suitable manner. Explain your choices in 50 words.

## Bounding Volume Hierarchy

Flags: features.enableAccelStructure, files: bvh.cpp

Flags: features.enableNormalInterp files: interpolate.h, interpolate.cpp.

The project comes with a compiled library to build the hierarchy and to perform the ray traversal in to find the intersection point. Hereby, you have immediately a reasonably fast ray tracer. Nevertheless, the traversal is still a feature that you are asked to implement yourself.

Methods

  • [3.00] - intersect(...), computeBarycentricCoord(...), interpolateNormal(...)/interpolateTexCoord(...) - The function intersect(...) (located in bvh.cpp) is where you should write your ray traversal. Currently, it calls intersectRayWithBVH, which is the call to the provided binary solution via the library.

Comment the call out and write your own hierarchy traversal to find the intersection point using the BVH data structure – starting at the root node and recursively testing children for intersections, whose children are visited, if the ray indeed intersects their geometry.

The provided solution does not determine the barycentric coordinates of the intersection point yet. Compute the barycentric coordinates of an intersection point in form of a vec3 with the barycentric coordinates (alpha, beta, gamma) in interpolate.cpp. In the same file, add the code to interpolate normals and texture coordinates, based on the computed barycentric coordinates. Call these functions from within your traversal code to set all entries of the hitInfo object to the correct value.

To render your function more robust, in case that the provided vertex is not on the triangle, find the closest point within the triangle and determine its barycentric coordinates.

Visual debug

[1.00] Visualize the ray traversal through the BVH – all intersection points, the order of the visited nodes, the visit node bounding boxes and the final intersected geometry. Think about a useful color scheme to render the illustration clear.

Texture mapping

Flags: features.enableTextureMapping, files: texture.h, texture.cpp, dependency: ray traversal and barycentric coordinates.

Support textures in the ray-tracer to give your rendered image a detailed look. Given texture coordinate data on the hitInfo object, you can perform texture lookups in a diffuse texture.

Methods

  • [0.25] - sampleTextureNearest(...) - Given an image and relevant texture coordinates, sample the texture s.t. the nearest texel to the coordinates is acquired from the image.

  • [0.50] - sampleTextureBilinear(...) - Given an image and relevant texture coordinates, sample the texture s.t. a bilinearly interpolated texel is acquired from the image.

Example renders

Visual debug tasks and reflection tasks

  • [2.00] - Implement a view of the texture space and how the geometry is mapped into it. Highlight the ray intersection position as well as the involved pixels from texture space.

Think about and show illustration for secondary hitpoints over several objects.

Lights and shadows

Flags: features.enableShadows, features.numShadowSamples, files: light.h, light.cpp, dependency: shading models.

In this feature, you will implement the contribution of lights and shadows. By default, the only light type that is supported is the point light as computeContributionPointLight(...) in light.cpp has a barebones implementation (which does not incorporate shadows). You will implement the following methods, and in doing so build towards a good setup for handling the three different light types (points, segments, and parallellograms) with both hard and soft shadows. We recommend that you implement them in the order given in this document.

Methods

  • [0.25] - sampleSegmentLight(...) - Given a single segment light, transform a uniformly distributed 1d sample in \([0, 1)\), into a uniformly sampled position and color on the segment light, and write these into the reference return values.

  • [0.50] - sampleParallelogramLight(...) - Given a single paralellogram light, transform a uniformly distributed 2d sample in \([0, 1),\) into a uniformly sampled position and color on the paralellogram light, and write these into the reference return values.

  • [0.25] - testVisibilityLightSampleBinary(...) - Given a sampled position on some light, and the emitted color at this position, return whether or not the light is visible from the provided ray/intersection.

  • [0.25] - computeContributionPointLight(...) - Given a single point light, compute its contribution towards an incident ray at an intersection point.

  • [0.50] - computeContributionSegmentLight(...)/computeContributionParallelogramLight(...) - Given a single segment/parallelogram light, compute its contribution towards an incident ray at an intersection point by integrating over the segment/parallelogram, taking numSamples samples.

  • [0.5] - testVisibilityLightSampleTransparency(...) - Given a sampled position on some light, and the emitted color at this position, return the light that is visible from the provided ray/intersection taking alpha-blending into account. Use the following blending operation: lightColor = lightColor * kd * (1 - transparency). (as another reminder: transparency is the same as alpha in the lectures).

Example renders

Visual debug tasks and reflection tasks

  • [0.50] - Visualize visibility rays and whether or not these pass/fail, as well as a visualization of the transparency.

  • [0.25] - Visualize the samples generated on your segment/parallelogram light, to verify they are uniformly distributed across the light.

  • [0.25] - Compare samples drawn with the provided sampler for 2D to the samples that you obtain by choosing both coordinates of a sample with the 1D random sampling. What do you observe? 20 words.

  • [1.75] - Reflect within 50 words in your report on why the blending operation used in the function testVisibilityLightSampleTransparency(...) (see above) is incorrect, based on the alpha blending derivation in the course. What would you propose how this could be modified? Illustrate an example of what is incorrect and, if possible, your proposal.

Multisampling

Flags: features.numPixelSamples, files: render.h, render.cpp.

To ensure that the image you render avoids aliasing, you must handle multisampling. While the ray-tracer by default renders pixels by sending a ray through the pixel’s center, you must now extend generatePixelRays() to support placement of multiple rays within a pixel. In addition, you must implement jittered sampling, where rays are randomly sampled from each cell in a grid across the pixel.

Methods

  • [0.25] - generatePixelRaysMultisampled(...) - Given a render state, camera, pixel position, and output resolution, generates a set of camera ray samples distributed uniformly across this pixel.

  • [0.75] - generatePixelRaysJittered(...) - Given a render state, camera, pixel position, and output resolution, generates a set of camera ray samples placed using jittered sampling throughout this pixel.

Example renders

Visual debug tasks and reflection tasks

  • [1.00] - Provide visualizations of the sample distribution within a pixel for the different approaches by drawing the grid over a pixel plus the respectively sampled positions. As a guidance, you can find an exemplary depiction in the Physically-based Rendering book (see Figure 8.24 on https://pbr-book.org/4ed/Sampling_and_Reconstruction/Stratified_Sampler). Discuss and explain the differences. (word limit: 100 words)

  • [1.25] - Provide visualizations of a scene for the different multisampling strategies and discuss the differences. Choose/make scenes and select settings to well illustrate the effects. What is the benefit of using jittering over using an unjittered sampling pattern? (word limit: 100 words)
